00:01:52.028 --> 00:01:53.442
by something else as well.

00:01:53.442 --> 00:01:55.415
The Shadow, for instance,[br]was partly inspired

00:01:55.415 --> 00:01:58.309
by Bram Stoker's Dracula,[br]which was partly inspired

00:01:58.309 --> 00:02:00.312
by Varney the Vampire, which, hey,

00:02:00.312 --> 00:02:03.331
also went around and[br]inspired a Marvel character

00:02:03.331 --> 00:02:05.979
named Varney the First Vampire.

00:02:05.979 --> 00:02:07.687
It's actually kind of a fun game,

00:02:07.687 --> 00:02:10.157
trying to backtrack[br]influences and inspirations,

00:02:10.157 --> 00:02:13.196
and it happens with[br]everything that people create.

00:02:13.196 --> 00:02:15.413
Take a look at this show[br]you're watching right now,

00:02:15.413 --> 00:02:18.084
the always wonderful Comic Misconceptions.

00:02:18.084 --> 00:02:19.952
My influences, probably obviously,

00:02:19.952 --> 00:02:22.133
were Variant, Idea Channel, Game Theory,

00:02:22.133 --> 00:02:24.446
Cracked, and a lot of others.

00:02:24.446 --> 00:02:26.353
And maybe that's the idea for creation

00:02:26.353 --> 00:02:28.829
to have lots of influences,[br]instead of just one.

00:02:28.829 --> 00:02:30.721
Perhaps that's what makes a rip-off

00:02:30.721 --> 00:02:32.648
seem less like a rip-off.

00:02:32.648 --> 00:02:33.934
Playwright Wilson Misener once said

00:02:33.934 --> 00:02:36.056
that if you copy from one[br]author, it's plagiarism.

00:02:36.056 --> 00:02:38.110
If you copy from two, it's research.

00:02:38.110 --> 00:02:41.712
Author Austin Kleon said[br]that art is 99% robbery,

00:02:41.712 --> 00:02:43.998
and even outlines what[br]is good and bad theft

00:02:43.998 --> 00:02:45.806
in his book, Steal Like An Artist.

00:02:45.806 --> 00:02:47.608
One of the key traits[br]is to steal from many

00:02:47.608 --> 00:02:50.912
while also being sure to transform[br]and remix what you steal.

00:02:50.912 --> 00:02:52.485
We've talked before about how the creators

00:02:52.485 --> 00:02:53.771
of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,

00:02:53.771 --> 00:02:56.566
Kevin Eastman and Peter[br]Laird, were openly copying

00:02:56.566 --> 00:02:58.266
and parodying other comics

00:02:58.266 --> 00:03:01.221
like Daredevil, Ronin,[br]New Mutants, and Cerebus.

00:03:01.221 --> 00:03:03.184
They took from many sources,

00:03:03.184 --> 00:03:04.957
while still giving it their own spin.

00:03:04.957 --> 00:03:07.084
And now, we have the[br]heroes in a half-shell,

00:03:07.084 --> 00:03:09.337
so obviously the stealing stuff works.

00:03:09.337 --> 00:03:11.902
But why is stealing even[br]necessary in the first place?

00:03:11.902 --> 00:03:14.283
Why don't comic book writers[br]and artists just come up

00:03:14.283 --> 00:03:16.240
with their own 100% original creation

00:03:16.240 --> 00:03:18.312
and avoid stealing altogether?

00:03:18.312 --> 00:03:19.827
Well, to put it frankly,

00:03:19.827 --> 00:03:22.530
there is no such thing as originality.

00:03:22.530 --> 00:03:25.159
As Kleon puts it, "Nothing[br]comes from nowhere.

00:03:25.159 --> 00:03:27.812
"All creative work builds[br]on what came before.

00:03:27.812 --> 00:03:30.087
"Nothing is completely original."

00:03:30.087 --> 00:03:31.980
Creativity requires influence.

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:34.125
You need a foundation of[br]knowledge and understanding

00:03:34.125 --> 00:03:36.755
before you can even begin to be creative.

00:03:36.755 --> 00:03:40.023
Musicians practice scales,[br]and cover other artists' songs

00:03:40.023 --> 00:03:41.666
before they can start making their own.

00:03:41.666 --> 00:03:44.251
Great authors read a lot, and so on.

00:03:44.251 --> 00:03:46.690
So is it really any surprise[br]that comic book writers

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:48.370
and artists are often accused of stealing

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:50.173
from other writers and artists?

00:03:50.173 --> 00:03:52.001
When you think about it comic books,

00:03:52.001 --> 00:03:55.839
at least how we know them[br]today, are fairly new art form.

00:03:55.839 --> 00:03:57.458
Where music dates back many millennia

00:03:57.458 --> 00:03:59.821
and it's had plenty of time[br]to evolve and branch off

00:03:59.821 --> 00:04:01.725
into drastically different genres,

00:04:01.725 --> 00:04:03.525
the comic on the other[br]hand only dates back

00:04:03.525 --> 00:04:06.598
to the 19th Century with superhero comics

00:04:06.598 --> 00:04:08.363
seeing a boom in the early 20th Century.

00:04:08.363 --> 00:04:10.386
And you really can't argue[br]that superhero comics are,

00:04:10.386 --> 00:04:13.367
by far, the most successful type of comic,

00:04:13.367 --> 00:04:16.073
especially during the[br]incredible Silver Age,

00:04:16.073 --> 00:04:18.386
when Marvel and DC[br]started dominating sales

00:04:18.386 --> 00:04:19.642
with their costumed characters,

00:04:19.642 --> 00:04:21.792
since the Comics Code[br]Authority helped shut down

00:04:21.792 --> 00:04:24.739
other popular genres, like[br]crime and horror comics.

00:04:24.739 --> 00:04:27.154
So when you have these[br]comic writers and artists

00:04:27.154 --> 00:04:29.859
who are all reading other[br]comics that predominantly

00:04:29.859 --> 00:04:32.262
feature superheroes, that's where

00:04:32.262 --> 00:04:34.327
they'll pull their inspiration from.

00:04:34.327 --> 00:04:36.678
If you're a musician, and[br]all you ever listen to

00:04:36.678 --> 00:04:38.671
is one genre, like Country music,

00:04:38.671 --> 00:04:40.245
then of course your songs

00:04:40.245 --> 00:04:42.172
are going to sound like Country music.

00:04:42.172 --> 00:04:44.224
You could copy elements[br]from different artists,

00:04:44.224 --> 00:04:45.803
but it's still gonna be Country,

00:04:45.803 --> 00:04:47.829
and the Internet is still[br]probably gonna make fun of you.

00:04:47.829 --> 00:04:49.661
When your list of influences is small,

00:04:49.661 --> 00:04:51.711
then your creations start to seem

00:04:51.711 --> 00:04:53.732
like rip-offs instead of remixes.

00:04:53.732 --> 00:04:56.340
Now simply acknowledging[br]that nothing is original

00:04:56.340 --> 00:04:58.421
and we all steal ideas from somewhere else

00:04:58.421 --> 00:05:00.424
sounds like a good idea in theory,

00:05:00.424 --> 00:05:01.522
it's nice in sentiment,

00:05:01.522 --> 00:05:04.001
but what if the tables were turned?

00:05:04.001 --> 00:05:05.595
What if you are the one being robbed?

00:05:05.595 --> 00:05:07.246
In his documentary, Everything is a Remix,

00:05:07.246 --> 00:05:09.439
Kirby Ferguson explains that people tend

00:05:09.439 --> 00:05:12.511
to put a higher value[br]on losses than gains.

00:05:12.511 --> 00:05:14.871
So when we steal from[br]others, it's no big deal.

00:05:14.871 --> 00:05:16.134
